<script type="text/javascript" src="/builds/ui/right-tooltips-min.js"></script>

<h1>Right Tooltips Demo</h1><% @title_text = "UI: Tooltips: Demo" %>

<style type="text/css">
  ul.tooltiped li {
    margin: .5em 0;
    cursor: pointer;
  }
  ul.tooltiped li:hover {
    background-color: #EEE;
  }
  
  #blue-tooltip div.right-tooltip-container {
    border-left-color: blue;
  }
  #green-tooltip div.right-tooltip-container {
    border-left-color: green;
  }
  #red-tooltip div.right-tooltip-container {
    border-left-color: red;
  }
</style>

<p>
  There are some use cases for the <%= link_to "right tooltips", '/ui/tooltips' %> widget
</p>

<h2>Simple Tooltips</h2>
<p>
  <ul class="tooltiped">
    <li title="Some tooltip" rel="tooltip">This element has a simple tooltip</li>
    <li title="Another tooltip" rel="tooltip">And this element has simple tooltip</li>
  </ul>
</p>

<h2>Tooltips With HTML</h2>
<p>
  If you need to put some html code into your tooltip, then just assign the escaped html code
  to the <tt>title</tt> attribute, it will work.
</p>
<code>
<li title="&amp;lt;b&amp;gt;Some&amp;lt;/b&amp;gt; &amp;lt;u&amp;gt;html&amp;lt;/u&amp;gt;">...</li>
</code>
<p>
  <ul class="tooltiped">
    <li title="&lt;b&gt;Some&lt;/b&gt; &lt;u&gt;html&lt;/u&gt; code" rel="tooltip">This has some html tooltip</li>
    <li title="&lt;s&gt;Another&lt;/s&gt; &lt;i&gt;html&lt;/i&gt; code" rel="tooltip">So does this one</li>
  </ul>
</p>

<h2>Tooltips On Images</h2>
<p>
  Images can has tooltips too. You can use ether <tt>title</tt> or <tt>alt</tt> attribute to keep the tooltip text.
</p>
<p>
  <img src="/images/test/1-thmb.jpg" rel="tooltip" title="Watson's Bay" />
  <img src="/images/test/2-thmb.jpg" rel="tooltip" alt="Some boats at Coogie" />
</p>

<h2>Customized Tooltips</h2>
<p>
  If an element has an <tt>id</tt> attribute then the related tooltip element will have the same <tt>id</tt>
  but with the <tt>-tooltip</tt> suffix, so you can customize them separately.
</p>
<p>
  <ul class="tooltiped">
    <li title="Blue Tooltip" rel="tooltip" id="blue">This one has blue tooltip</li>
    <li title="Green Tooltip" rel="tooltip" id="green">This one has green tooltip</li>
    <li title="Red Tooltip" rel="tooltip" id="red">This one has red tooltip</li>
  </ul>
</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>
  See the <%= link_to "tooltips documentation", "/ui/tooltips" %> for more details and options.
</p>